objects.name: Facilities engineer
objects.description: Facilities engineers in the petroleum business are responsible for planning, implementing, and maintaining the infrastructure and equipment of buildings and facilities in the petroleum industry. They perform analyses of operational processes, resource allocation, energy use, and safety processes, and recommend and implement improvements. They also perform facilities and operations documentation reviews and updates to facilitate process safety assessment, project execution, and operational process improvements.

objects.name: Geologist
objects.description:
A geologist is a scientist who studies the solid, liquid, and gaseous matter that constitutes Earth and other terrestrial planets, as well as the processes that shape them
1. Geologists usually study geology, earth science, or geophysics
2, although backgrounds in physics, chemistry, biology, and other sciences are also useful
.3 Geologists work to understand the history of the planet we live on, to better predict the future, and to explain current occurrences
4. They are also hired to survey land and draw up safe building plans3.

objects.name: Geophysicist
objects.description: Geophysics is a subject of natural science concerned with the physical processes and physical properties of the Earth and its surrounding space environment, and the use of quantitative methods for their analysis1. Geophysicists study how the Earth behaves, including earthquakes, erosion, volcanoes, and more2. They also explore the land’s past and present geology in order to predict its future2. Geophysicists measure, examine, and explore the physical properties of earth, from below the ground to the atmosphere, from the depths of the ocean to the tops of volcanoes3.

objects.name: Mature and Rank Target
objects.description: “Mature” and “Rank” are terms used in the oil and gas industry to describe the process of selecting the best drilling targets for a possible wellbore. The process involves analyzing geological data to determine the most promising areas for oil and gas exploration. The term “mature” refers to areas that have already been explored and have known reserves. The term “rank” refers to the process of prioritizing potential drilling targets based on their geological characteristics.

objects.name: Petrophysicist
objects.description: Petrophysics is the study of physical and chemical rock properties and their interactions with fluids1. In the oil and gas industry, the geologist and the geophysicist set out to define a reservoir prospect target from a structural perspective, while the petrophysicist fills in the details regarding the rock properties and fluid content of the reservoir2. Petrophysicists work together with reservoir engineers and other professionals to determine how much oil or gas can be extracted from a given reservoir1.

objects.name: Production engineer
objects.description: Production engineers in the petroleum business are responsible for designing and implementing methods to extract oil and gas from deposits below the Earth’s surface. They work with geologists and other specialists to understand the geologic formation of the reservoir and determine the best method to extract the resources. They also monitor production rates and optimize production by adjusting well flow rates, implementing new technologies, and improving recovery methods.

objects.name: Reservoir engineer
objects.description: Reservoir engineers are responsible for the management of oil and gas reservoirs. They work with a variety of different companies, from small independents to large multinational corporations. Their job is to ensure that these companies have access to as much hydrocarbon resources as possible. Reservoir engineering is a branch of petroleum engineering that applies scientific principles to the fluid flow through porous medium during the development and production of oil and gas reservoirs so as to obtain a high economic recovery.

objects.name: Subsurface Team
objects.description:
A subsurface team is a multidisciplinary team that manages production for a field and looks for ways of getting more hydrocarbons out of that field. In a large company, this team will include some combination of the job titles listed in the table below:

- Geologist
- Geophysicist
- Petrophysicist
- Reservoir engineer
- Production engineer
- Facilities engineer

objects.name: Subsurface Team Lead
objects.description:
1. The Subsurface Team Lead is responsible for leading a group of cross-functional technical staff supporting the three regionally organized subsurface teams 
2. The Subsurface Team Lead maximizes the value of assets by delivering business plan targets through project delivery, resource maturation and management 
3. They are also responsible for managing multi-disciplinary teams delivering reservoir optimization, management and development activities for mature North Sea assets
